      %h3
        FABRIC AND KNIT - KNOW YOUR WOOLS

      .article-image.aspect-4-5
        -image_url = image_path("blog/winter-jumpers/cream-jumper-cross-legged.jpg")
        =image_tag(image_url, alt: "A lady sits cross-legged on an armchair. She wears a cream cashmere jumper with a high loose neck and sits on a warm knitted throw.")
        %figcaption
          Photo by
          =link_to('ArthurHidden', 'https://www.freepik.com/free-photo/smiling-lady-smart-trendy-wear-is-sitting-armchair-smiling-sitting-relaxing-atmosphere-indoors_13085112.htm')
          on Freepik

      %p
        There is one main reason why winter jumpers are made of wool.
        It keeps you warm.
        That is literally it! Wool’s natural construction is designed with this one main purpose in mind.
        Take a look at sheep.
        Just before they are shorn, they look pretty snug and how do their coats look?
        Very warm indeed.
        And this is what is all about.

      %p
        Wool is so warm naturally, but it is woven in such a way that it traps even more heat and this is basically why we love it in winter.
        Did you know that there are different grades of wool too?
        Did you know that there are even different weights of wool?
        These attributes all go to define the quality of the jumper you will end up with.

      %p
        So, do you know what wool to look for and what to avoid?
        Do you know your loose knits from your tight weaves, or your chunky knits from your fine ones?
        What about those soft and luxurious knits that we all love the feel of?
        Do you know which fine animal they came from?

      %p
        Well, to help you understand a little more about wool, I have added a simple chart below.
        This covers the top and most sought-after wools and the standards that most wools are graded by.

      %p
        So, let's take a look at what type of wools to look out for.

